snippet.textDisplay:
Wow. Going through this list now, years after it was uploaded, and I still got feels from this. Supra deserves a medal. This is so compelling not jut because it provides examples of people enjoying great videogames, but because of the sheer variety of the games displayed. It exemplifies the notion that videogames really are a universal pleasure, and that it's possible for everyone to find a game they love.

Also, I always prefer to think that Itoi doesn't say "I miss you" at the end, but rather *_"I'll_* miss you." It's as if he knows that the game is drawing to a close, and that once the credits finish rolling, you are likely to never pick the game up ever again. This can be said for a lot games, and is why finishing a game always brings about feelings of accomplishment and melancholy. Truly, smiles and tears.

"no story"

They do have a story, but yes, they tended to re-hash the same basic one over and over for a while(legendary of the game being awakened, evil "team" group, etc.). But honestly, Pokemon was never meant to be new or innovative after the first 1 or 2 titles. People want to catch new pokemon and be the champ. In this way, the games deliver.
